definition.value: A member of the class of monochlorobenzenes that is benzene substituted by 2-(1,3-dinitrilopropan-2-ylidene)hydrazinyl and chloro groups at positions 1 and 3, respectively. It is a mitochondrial depolarizing agent that induces reactive oxygen species mediated cell death.
A group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of alpha-D-mannosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-mannose.
A magnesium salt having sulfate as the counterion.
An acene that consists of four ortho-fused benzene rings in a rectilinear arrangement.
A group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of 2,4,6-tris(N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl)-alpha-D-mannose.
The L-enantiomer of isoleucinate.
The L-enantiomer of isoleucinium.
The D-enantiomer of isoleucinate.
The D-enantiomer of isoleucinium.
An azacycloalkane that is cycloheptane in which one of the carbon atoms is replaced by a nitrogen atom.
A group obtained by removing the hydroxy group from the hemiacetal function of N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannosyl-(1->3)-beta-D-mannose.
The L-enantiomer of leucinate.
The L-enantiomer of leucinium.
The D-enantiomer of leucinate.
The D-enantiomer of leucinium.
An alkane-alpha,omega-diammonium(2+) that is the dication of putrescine (1,4-butanediamine) arising from protonation of both primary amino groups; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of leucine, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
An alpha-amino-acid cation that is the conjugate acid of leucine, arising from protonation of the amino group.
The L-enantiomer of  methioninate.
The L-enantiomer of methioninium.
An aryl sulfate that is paracetamol in which the hydroxy group has been replaced by a sulfooxy group.
A beta-D-glucosiduronic acid that is the O-glucuronide of paracetamol (acetaminophen).
The D-enantiomer of methioninate.
The D-enantiomer of methioninium.
